I guess I didn't read it closely enough the first time, but now we have to
consider that it might be accepted...

This seems wrong:

http://sac.sfbay.sun.com/Archives/CaseLog/arc/FWARC/2006/115/materials/spec.txt

	2. At the time control is transferred to the callback function in
	   POST (at POST_PA + 0xC0), the address of the control transfer
	   instruction should be saved in %o7 register. POST would use this
	   address (%o7+4) to return to OpenBoot after completing the callback
	   function.

The normal return from a jmpl (or call) is to (%o7 + 8) - is POST being
different or is this a typo? (the 'ret' and 'retl' synthetic instructions
expand to 'jmpl %i7 +8, %g0' and 'jmpl %o7 + 8'

This is also odd:

    4.1.5  POST Callback Functions

...

	Following registers are modified by the POST callback function :

	%o0-%o7

Since %o6 is setup as a stack for the call into POST (documented below in
the spec.), is it true that OBP has to restore %o6 after POST
returns?

More:

	4. Machine state at the time of callback is :

	    %y			0

Does OBP actually ensure this is the case? It seems doubtful
since %y is treated like %g# over a function call.

	    Alternate global registers, Interrupt global registers,
	    MMU global registers, Floating point registers, local
	    registers are undefined.

Why are the local registers mentioned here? In a function call, the %o#
'outs' are for the function being called and - by convention - the function
does not touch the %l# locals or %i# 'ins'.

-------------
Given that we are re-opening the case, these items need to be resolved before
it is closed again.

Tony.



